text: Temperature impairments were assessed within Peterson Creek using a combination of in-stream
label: BODY

text: temperature measurements, riparian shading assessments, mid-summer streamflow
label: BODY

text: measurements, and modeling.  The Peterson Creek temperature assessment was conducted to aid
label: BODY

text: in the development of Total Maximum Daily Loads (TMDLs) in the Upper Clark Fork TMDL
label: BODY

text: Planning Area (TPA).  Data collected during this assessment were used in the QUAL2K model
label: BODY

text: to assess the influence of shading and streamflow on stream temperatures in Peterson Creek.
label: BODY

text: The results of this assessment were compared to Montana’s water quality standards for
label: BODY

text: temperature to evaluate beneficial use support and potential restoration strategies.
label: BODY

text: Montana’s water quality standard for temperature addresses a maximum allowable increase
label: BODY

text: above the “naturally occurring” temperature to protect the existing thermal regime for fish and
label: BODY

text: aquatic life.  For waters classified as B-1, the maximum allowable increase over the naturally
label: BODY

text: occurring temperature (if the naturally occurring temperature is less than 66º Fahrenheit) is 1°F.
label: BODY

text: In the naturally occurring range of 66-66.5 ºF, an increase cannot exceed 67ºF.  If the naturally
label: BODY

text: occurring temperature is greater than 66.5ºF, the maximum allowable increase is 0.5º F [ARM
label: BODY

text: 17.30.622(e) and ARM 17.30.623(e)].  Temperature monitoring and modeling indicated that
label: BODY

text: naturally occurring stream temperatures in Peterson Creek are likely greater than 66.5°F during
label: BODY

text: portions of the summer months.  Thus, the maximum allowable increase due to unmitigated
label: BODY

text: The Peterson Creek temperature assessment was performed in order to identify existing
label: BODY

text: conditions and to determine if anthropogenic disturbances have led to increased stream water
label: BODY

text: temperatures.  This assessment utilized field data and computer modeling to assess stream
label: BODY

text: temperatures in relation to Montana’s water quality standards.
label: BODY

text: Field data used in this assessment were collected by Montana DEQ staff during the 2007 field
label: BODY

text: season and included temperature measurements, streamflow measurements, and an assessment of
label: BODY

text: riparian shading along Peterson Creek and selected tributaries.  Field methods are described in
label: BODY

text: Upper Clark Fork TMDL Planning Area Temperature and Instantaneous Flow Monitoring
label: BODY

text: Temperature monitoring was conducted on Peterson Creek over a two-month timeframe in the
label: BODY

text: summer of 2007.  The study timeframe examined stream temperatures during the period when
label: BODY

text: streamflows tend to be lowest, water temperatures are warmest, and negative affects to the cold
label: BODY

text: water fishery and aquatic life beneficial uses are likely most pronounced.  Temperature
label: BODY

text: monitoring consisted of placing temperature data logging devices at 11 sites in the Peterson
label: BODY

text: Creek watershed during the summer of 2007.  Temperature monitoring sites were selected to
label: BODY

text: bracket stream reaches with similar hydrology, riparian vegetation type, valley type, stream
label: BODY

text: aspect, and channel width so that the temperature data collected during this assessment could be
label: BODY

text: utilized in the QUAL2K model.  A summary of temperature data is presented in Attachment A.
label: BODY

text: Streamflow was measured at 11 sites on Peterson Creek and selected tributary streams where
label: BODY

text: temperature data logging devices were deployed.  Streamflow data were collected during
label: BODY

text: temperature data logger deployment and again during retrieval.  Streamflow data collected
label: BODY

text: during this assessment were used in the QUAL2K model to help determine if in-stream
label: BODY

text: temperatures exceed Montana standards.  Streamflow data is presented in Attachment B.
label: BODY

text: Riparian shading was assessed at five sites along Peterson Creek using a Solar Pathfinder which
label: BODY

text: measures the amount of shade at a site in one-hour intervals.  The Solar Pathfinder was utilized
label: BODY

text: to assess riparian shading using the August template for the path of the sun.  Shade was
label: BODY

text: measured three times over a 200-foot reach at each site.  In addition to the Solar Pathfinder
label: BODY

text: readings, the following measurements were performed at each site in which riparian shading was
label: BODY

text: The QUAL2K model was used to determine if human caused disturbances within the watershed
label: BODY

text: have increased the water temperature above the “naturally occurring” level and, if so, to what
label: BODY

text: degree.  The QUAL2K model is available at:
label: BODY

text: and streamflow data collected in the summer of 2007 were used to calibrate the QUAL2K model
label: BODY

text: for existing conditions.  The potential to reduce stream temperatures was then modeled based on
label: BODY

text: Data sources and model assumptions made during this assessment include:
label: BODY

text: 1. Temperature data loggers were placed at 11 sites in the Peterson Creek watershed during
label: BODY

text: the summer of 2007, including eight mainstem locations and three tributaries.  Data
label: BODY

text: loggers were deployed between July 16th and 18th and retrieved on September 26th.  One
label: BODY

text: mainstem temperature data logger was lost (PTR-04) and one tributary data logger did
label: BODY

text: not work properly (PTR-02) resulting in temperature data for seven Peterson Creek sites
label: BODY

text: and two tributary streams (Table 2-1).  The maximum daily temperature and the 7-day
label: BODY

text: average maximum temperature data were reviewed to identify the warmest day of the
label: BODY

text: season.  Maximum daily temperatures occurred between July 19th and 28th, depending on
label: BODY

text: the site, while the 7-day average maximum temperature occurred between July 20th and
label: BODY

text: 22nd (Attachment A).  Based on this data set, the QUAL2K model was run for July 21st,
label: BODY

text: 2. Streamflow data were collected at 11 sites during temperature data logger deployment
label: BODY

text: and retrieval, with eight measurements on Peterson Creek and three measurements on
label: BODY

text: tributary streams (Table 2-1, Attachment B).  Streamflows collected during data logger
label: BODY

text: deployment were applied in the QUAL2K model since the deployment date (July 16th –
label: BODY

text: 18th) was near the date for which maximum temperatures were modeled (July 21st).

text: 3. Streamside shading was assessed at five sites corresponding to the location of
label: BODY

text: temperature data loggers.  Four sites were located on Peterson Creek, while one site was
label: BODY

text: located on a headwater tributary stream.  Riparian shade was assessed using the August
label: BODY

text: template for the solar pathfinder, which measures the amount of shade at one-hour
label: BODY

text: intervals.  Since the QUAL2K model was run for July 21st, shade measurements based on
label: BODY

text: the August path of the sun may be slightly higher than the actual shade on July 21st due to
label: BODY

text: the fact that sun is slightly lower in the sky during August than during July.  However,
label: BODY

text: based on the relatively small size of the riparian shade dataset, any additional error
label: BODY

text: introduced based on slightly different sun angles in July and August is likely negligible.
label: BODY

text: At each site where shade was assessed, the riparian vegetation type was also described
label: BODY

text: and the average daily shade at each site was calculated (Table 2-2).  Average daily shade
label: BODY

text: ranged from 34% at PTR-08 to 92% at PTR-07.  The majority of the solar pathfinder
label: BODY

text: measurements documented relatively dense shrub cover which was observed along much
label: BODY

text: of Peterson Creek and measured at sites PTR-03, PTR-04 and PTR-07.  Forested
label: BODY

text: conditions in the headwaters were documented at the PTR-02 site, while open pasture
label: BODY

text: conditions in areas of irrigated agriculture were documented at the PTR-08 site.

text: Once the above calibration steps were performed, the QUAL2K model was run for the baseline
label: BODY

text: scenario which is intended to represent existing conditions in Peterson Creek on July 21st, 2007
label: BODY

text: (Figure 2-2).  This model run utilized all measured field data, with the assumptions described in
label: BODY

text: Section 2.2.1 of this document.  The model failed to accurately predict the dramatic increase in
label: HH2

text: temperatures that were actually measured between sites PTR-01 and PTR-03 at the upper end of
label: BODY

text: Peterson Creek.  Poor model calibration between sites PTR-01 and PTR-03 was thought to be
label: BODY

text: primarily due to the small size of this stream relative to the influence of riparian shading.
label: BODY

text: Hydraulic output in the model accurately reflected measured conditions, indicating that water
label: BODY

text: routing and channel morphology were adequately calibrated.  Several additional model
label: BODY

text: calibration steps were taken in an attempt to increase temperatures between site PTR-01 and
label: BODY

text: PTR-03.  Decreasing shade to 0% was required to accomplish this task.  Since this appeared
label: BODY

text: unrealistic based on a review of aerial imagery and on-the-ground observations, the decision was
label: BODY

text: made to retain the baseline scenario as depicted in Figure 2-2 with the understanding that it does
label: BODY

text: not accurately represent temperature values measured in the field, especially in the upper reaches
label: BODY

text: of Peterson Creek.  Model scenarios were compared to the results of the baseline model and not
label: BODY

text: to the field measured values to assure consistency when evaluating the potential to reduce stream

text: When applying the QUAL2K model in temperature assessments, a channel morphology scenario
label: BODY

text: that examines the influence of channel over-widening is often applied.  However, field data
label: BODY

text: collected in 2007 documented low width/depth ratios, suggesting there was minimal potential to
label: BODY

text: further reduce stream channel width.  Thus, the channel morphology modeling scenario was not
label: BODY

text: applied to the Peterson Creek temperature assessment.
label: BODY

text: The water consumptive use scenario describes the thermal effect of irrigation and domestic water
label: BODY

text: uses on water temperatures in Peterson Creek.  This scenario was modeled by removing existing
label: BODY

text: water diversions from the study reach as identified in the hydrologic balance (Table 2-5).  The
label: BODY

text: current modeling effort included irrigation withdrawals identified in three reaches: PCT5, PCT7
label: BODY

text: and PCT9.  Warm water irrigation return flows were also removed from reaches PCT5 and
label: BODY

text: PCT7.  Additional irrigation withdrawals not identified through field measurements in 2007 may
label: BODY

text: be present, but were not accounted for in this modeling exercise.  These included observed
label: BODY

text: withdrawals in reaches PCT2 and PCT6.  All other parameters from the baseline scenario were
label: BODY

text: retained.  This scenario indicated that water withdrawals have a lesser potential impact on stream
label: BODY

text: temperatures than riparian shading (Figure 2-5).  The model indicated that slight decreases in
label: BODY

text: temperature could be achieved through water conservation in reach PCT6 upstream of the
label: BODY

text: confluence with Burnt Hollow Creek and reach PCT9 through the City of Deer Lodge.  Due to a
label: BODY

text: lack of measurements of irrigation withdrawals throughout the system, the results of the water
label: BODY

text: consumptive use scenario should be interpreted with caution.  If more detailed flow data for the
label: BODY

text: irrigation network becomes available, this scenario may need to be reevaluated.

text: The natural condition scenario reflects the temperature regime that would be expected absent of
label: BODY

text: the influence of man.  This allows for the characterization of the extent of the departure from the
label: BODY

text: natural condition.  Factors applied in shade scenario 1 (reference shade) and the water
label: BODY

text: consumptive use scenario (no irrigation withdrawals) were applied to run this scenario.  All other
label: BODY

text: parameters from the baseline scenario were retained.  The natural condition scenario indicated
label: BODY

text: that maximum temperatures at the mouth of Peterson Creek could be approximately 15°F cooler
label: BODY

text: than the modeled maximum temperature of 78.3°F (Figure 2-6).  The measured maximum
label: BODY

text: temperature on July 21st of 2007 was 75.8°F at the mouth (PTR-14), while the natural condition
label: BODY

text: scenario results in a maximum temperature of 62.7°F (Attachment D), suggesting water
label: BODY

text: temperatures could be approximately 13°F cooler at the mouth of Peterson Creek.  The seasonal
label: BODY

text: maximum value at site PTR-14 was 78.0°F on July 22nd (Attachment A).

text: The naturally occurring scenario defines water temperature conditions resulting from the
label: BODY

text: implementation of all reasonable land, soil and water conservation practices as outlined in ARM
label: BODY

text: 17.30.602.  This scenario identifies the “naturally occurring” temperature in water bodies of
label: BODY

text: interest and establishes the temperatures to which a 0.23°C (0.5°F) temperature increase is
label: BODY

text: allowable.  This, in turn, can be used to identify the impairment status of a water body.  This
label: BODY

text: scenario included improved shading in reaches PCT6 and PCT9 as suggested by shade scenario 2
label: BODY

text: along with a 15% increase in irrigation and domestic water use efficiency.  This was calculated
label: BODY

text: by reducing the three identified irrigation withdrawals by 15%.  The result of the naturally
label: BODY

text: occurring scenario was similar to the result of shade scenario 2, with substantial reductions in
label: BODY

text: temperature predicted in Peterson Creek downstream of the confluence with Jack Creek.  Based
label: BODY

text: on the naturally occurring scenario, a maximum temperature of 68.6°F was predicted at the
label: BODY

text: mouth of Peterson Creek and there is the potential for an approximately 10°F reduction in in-
label: BODY

text: stream temperatures relative to the baseline scenario (Attachment D).

text: 2.3 Peterson Creek Modeled Temperature Relative to Montana Standards
label: HH1

text: The naturally occurring scenario indicated that water temperatures greater than 66.5°F can be
label: BODY

text: expected in Peterson Creek.  Thus, the maximum allowable increase in temperature due to
label: BODY

text: unmitigated human causes is 0.5°F (0.23°C) (see Section 1.1).  This standard was exceeded at
label: BODY

text: the lower-most four monitoring sites on Peterson Creek, which represents Peterson Creek from
label: BODY

text: downstream of Jack Creek to the confluence with the Clark Fork River (Table 2-6, results for
label: BODY

text: each modeling scenario presented in Attachment D).  The majority of the temperature reduction
label: BODY

text: potential predicted by the QUAL2K model resulted from increased shade, as presented in shade
label: BODY

text: scenario 2 (Figure 2-4), with an additional smaller reduction in temperatures resulting from
label: BODY

text: improved irrigation and domestic water management.  As discussed in Section 2.2.3, the
label: BODY

text: dramatic modeled temperature reductions were likely a result of the minimal flow in this small
label: BODY

text: stream.  Due to the minimal amount of flow, there may be a substantial amount of error in the
label: BODY

text: QUAL2K model.  However, temperature data collected in 2007 and the results of this QUAL2K
label: BODY

text: modeling effort suggest that Peterson Creek fails to meet Montana’s standard for temperature
label: BODY

text: during low flow periods in the middle of summer and that an increase in riparian shading,
label: BODY

text: particularly along reaches PCT6 and PCT9 will likely lead to a decrease in water temperatures.
label: BODY

text: This assessment indicated that Peterson Creek is impaired due to elevated water temperatures
label: BODY

text: during low flow periods in the middle of summer.  Overall, the results of this study indicated that
label: BODY

text: Peterson Creek downstream of the confluence with Jack Creek should be the focus of restoration
label: BODY

text: efforts directed towards decreasing water temperatures in Peterson Creek.
label: BODY

text: Major findings and restoration recommendations include:
label: BODY

text: Temperature data collected in 2007 and the results of this QUAL2K modeling
label: BODY

text: effort suggest that Peterson Creek fails to meet Montana’s standard for
label: BODY

text: temperature during low flow periods in the middle of summer.
label: BODY

text: Modeling indicated that increased shading in reaches PCT6 and PCT9 would
label: BODY

text: likely have the greatest impact on water temperatures in Peterson Creek.  Reach
label: BODY

text: PCT6 extends upstream of the Burnt Hollow Creek confluence, while Reach
label: BODY

text: PCT9 flows through the town of Deer Lodge.  In 2007, maximum temperatures
label: BODY

text: were observed at site PTR-12 in reach PCT7, which is located downstream of the
label: BODY

text: Burnt Hollow Creek confluence.  This further supports the need for improved
label: BODY

text: riparian shading upstream of this site.
label: BODY

text: Maximum streamflows were observed at PTR-12, which is located downstream of
label: BODY

text: the Burnt Hollow Creek confluence.  Streamflows decreased by 80% between this
label: BODY

text: site and the confluence with the Clark Fork River.  Thus, irrigation efficiency
label: BODY

text: improvements should focus on Peterson Creek downstream of the confluence with
label: BODY

text: Limitations of this study include a lack of detailed flow measurements for the irrigation network,
label: BODY

text: a lack of reference conditions data for riparian shading, and potential limitations of the QUAL2K
label: BODY

text: model when working with such a small stream.  Thus, the results of this assessment may need to
label: BODY

text: be reevaluated as additional information becomes available.
